# PR Workflow

Invoke with: *"open pr"*, *"create pr"*, *"pr flow"*, *"prepare PR"*, *"ready for review"*

Complete workflow from branch creation through quality gates to opening a PR.

---

## 1. Pre-Flight Checklist

Before starting the PR flow, verify:

- [ ] All requirements met, edge cases handled
- [ ] No TODO comments without context, no commented-out code, no debug code
- [ ] Loading / error / empty states in all new React pages
- [ ] `validateBody` on all new POST routes
- [ ] Shared types used (not duplicated across packages)
- [ ] No cross-package imports (client cannot import server)

---

## 2. Ask for PR Details

- **Branch name**: suggest based on recent changes (e.g., `feat/add-readiness-page`)
- **Commit message**: suggest based on modified files, use conventional format
- **PR title**: default to commit message
- Confirm with user before proceeding

---

## 3. Create Branch and Commit

```bash
git checkout -b <branch-name>
git add -A
git commit -m "<commit-message>"
```

Use conventional commit format: `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `chore:`, `docs:`

---

## 4. Run ALL Quality Gates

Run every check **before pushing**. If any step fails, stop and fix.

```bash
# Lint (zero warnings enforced)
npm run lint

# Format check
npm run format:check

# Unused code detection
npm run knip

# Build shared first (other packages depend on it)
npm run build -w packages/shared

# Type check all packages
npm run typecheck -w packages/shared
npm run typecheck -w packages/server
npx tsc --noEmit -p packages/client/tsconfig.json

# Build server
npm run build -w packages/server

# Run tests
npm run test

# Build client (includes tsc + vite build)
npm run build -w packages/client
```

ALL must pass. If any fails:
1. Show the error
2. Fix the issue
3. Re-run the failing step
4. Only proceed when all pass

---

## 5. Rebase on Main

```bash
git fetch origin main
git rebase origin/main
```

If rebase has conflicts, stop and ask the user to resolve.

---

## 6. Push the Branch

```bash
git push -u origin <branch-name> --force-with-lease
```

NEVER force push to `main` or `master`.

---

## 7. Open PR

```bash
gh pr create --title "<pr-title>" --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
## Summary
<auto-generated from commit message and changed files>

## Changes
- packages/shared: [what changed]
- packages/server: [what changed]
- packages/client: [what changed]

## Quality Gates
- [x] ESLint (0 errors, 0 warnings)
- [x] Prettier formatting clean
- [x] Knip (no unused files/deps/exports)
- [x] TypeScript (shared + server + client)
- [x] Tests pass
- [x] Build succeeds

## Test Plan
- [ ] Server starts without errors
- [ ] Client builds and loads
- [ ] Key features verified locally
EOF
)"
```

---

## 8. PR State Check

Before pushing to an existing PR branch:

1. Check if PR is still open: `gh pr view <number> --json state -q '.state'`
2. If `MERGED` or `CLOSED`: do NOT push. Create a new branch from main.
3. If `OPEN`: safe to push/amend.

**Never push to a merged PR branch.**

---

## 9. Post-PR

- Print the PR URL
- Stay on the feature branch (don't switch back to main)
- If CI fails, check with: `gh pr checks <number>`

---

## 10. Important Rules

- **NEVER push directly to `main`** -- ALL changes go through a PR, no exceptions
- NEVER force push to `main` or `master`
- ALWAYS create a feature branch first, even for single-line fixes
- ALWAYS run all quality gates before pushing
- ALWAYS rebase on latest main before opening PR
- Use `--force-with-lease` (not `--force`) after rebase
- PR body should summarize actual changes from the diff, not generic text
- After PR is created, stay on the feature branch
